        <summary><strong>3. COMPLAINT: ITCHING</strong></summary>
        <ol>
          <strong>S: Site (Location of itching)</strong>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Scalp</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Seborrheic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                  <li>Tinea capitis</li>
                  <li>Head lice (Pediculosis capitis)</li>
                  <li>Folliculitis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Face</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis (eczema)</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Rosacea</li>
                  <li>Perioral dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Seborrheic dermatitis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Neck</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Lichen simplex chronicus</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Chest</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Pityriasis rosea</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                  <li>Urticaria (hives)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Back</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                  <li>Folliculitis</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Abdomen</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Pityriasis rosea</li>
                  <li>Urticaria</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Groin</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Tinea cruris (jock itch)</li>
                  <li>Intertrigo</li>
                  <li>Candidiasis</li>
                  <li>Inverse psoriasis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Genital Area</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Candidiasis</li>
                  <li>Scabies</li>
                  <li>Lichen sclerosus</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Buttocks</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Intertrigo</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                  <li>Folliculitis</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Hands</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Scabies</li>
                  <li>Dyshidrotic eczema</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Knee</strong></li>
              <ul>
                <li><span style="color: #09a8cc;">back of knee - eczems</span></li>
                <li><span style=" color: #09a8cc;">front of knee<br>
                  </span></li>
              </ul>
              <li><strong>Feet</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Athlete's foot (Tinea pedis)</li>
                  <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                  <li>Dyshidrotic eczema</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Nails</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Onychomycosis</li>
                  <li>Psoriasis</li>
                  <li>Lichen planus</li>
                  <li>Paronychia</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>O: Onset (Rapid or chronic)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Sudden (acute) onset may suggest allergic reactions, insect
                bites, or infections.</li>
              <li>Gradual (chronic) onset may indicate underlying skin
                conditions like eczema or psoriasis.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>D: Duration (How long the itching has been present)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Acute: Less than 6 weeks (e.g., allergic reactions, insect
                bites).</li>
              <li>Chronic: More than 6 weeks (e.g., atopic dermatitis,
                psoriasis).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>A: Aggravating factors (What makes the itching worse)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Allergens (e.g., soaps, detergents, fabrics)</li>
              <li>Environmental factors (e.g., heat, cold, humidity)</li>
              <li>Time of day (e.g., worse at night)</li>
              <li>Physical activity or sweating</li>
              <li>Stress or anxiety</li>
              <li>Water exposure (e.g., bathing, swimming)</li>
              <li>Sunlight exposure</li>
              <li>weekends</li>
              <li>weekdays</li>
              <li>any particualar days</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong><strong>R: Relieveing (What improves the itching)</strong></strong>
            <div class="section">
              <ul>
                <li>Moisturizers or emollients</li>
                <li>Cold compresses or ice packs</li>
                <li>Antihistamines or topical steroids</li>
                <li>Avoiding triggers (e.g., certain fabrics, allergens)</li>
                <li>weekends</li>
                <li>weekdays</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <strong>C: Character/Type (Description of the itching sensation)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Pruritic (general itching)</li>
              <li>Burning or stinging sensation</li>
              <li>Crawling or tingling feeling</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>R: Radiation <br>
            </strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>A: Associated symptoms (Other symptoms accompanying
              the itching)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Rash or skin changes (e.g., redness, swelling, scaling)</li>
              <li>Discharge or oozing</li>
              <li>Pain or tenderness</li>
              <li>Fever or flu-like symptoms</li>
              <li>Fatigue or body aches</li>
              <li>Weight loss or loss of appetite (in systemic conditions)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>P: Progression (How the itching has changed over
              time)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Worsening, improving, or staying the same</li>
              <li>Spreading to other areas or remaining localized</li>
              <li>Changes in intensity or frequency</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>P: Pattern (Distribution and characteristics of
              itching)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Localized (confined to one area)</li>
              <li>Generalized (widespread across the body)</li>
              <li>Symmetrical or asymmetrical distribution</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>E: Effect on life (Impact on daily activities and
              quality of life)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Disruption of sleep</li>
              <li>Difficulty concentrating or working</li>
              <li>Social or emotional distress</li>
              <li>Skin damage from scratching</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <summary><strong>S: Scale of zero to 10 (Severity of itching)</strong></summary>
          <div class="section">
            <ul>
              <li>Rate the intensity of itching on a scale from 0 (no itching)
                to 10 (worst itching imaginable). </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </ol>
      </details>
